TT 1827 "AMICIA ĐÃ BỊ PHÁT HIỆN" GAME__ALERT_AMICIA
TT 1828 "HUGO ĐÃ BỊ PHÁT HIỆN" GAME__ALERT_HUGO
TT 1829 "HUGO ĐÃ BỊ BẮT" GAME__CAPTURE_HUGO
TT 1830 "Thảo Mộc của Hugo" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1
TT 1831 "Description of the category" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_DESC
TT 1832 "Hoa Cúc" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_1
TT 1833 "Hoa cúc là biểu tượng cho sự trong sáng và thuần khiết, phần vì màu trắng tinh khôi của những cánh hoa. Loài hoa này thường được dùng để sắc thuốc, thanh lọc cơ thể và trị chứng khó tiêu, cũng như tăng khả năng lành sẹo. Lá hoa cúc cũng từng được dùng trong món salad trên bàn ăn của cả quý tộc lẫn thường dân, nhờ vị cay nhè nhẹ của nó." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_1_DESC
TT 1834 "Hoa Cẩm Chướng" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_2
TT 1835 "Nó còn được gọi là “đóa hoa của Chúa” trong một số ngôn ngữ khác. Có vài người cho rằng tên gọi đó xuất phát từ vẻ đẹp của nó, một số khác lại lưu truyền rằng loài hoa này được sinh ra từ máu của Chúa Kito hoặc nước mắt của Đức Mẹ Đồng Trinh Maria. Do đó, nó là hiện thân của tình yêu, niềm đam mê và sự vĩnh cửu. Chiết xuất cánh hoa được sử dụng để hạ sốt nhờ khả năng tăng tiết mồ hôi, giấm ủ từ cánh hoa được dùng để điều trị mụn nước, góp phần khiến nó trở nên nổi tiếng." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_2_DESC
TT 1836 "Hoa Hoàng Liên Tím" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_3
TT 1837 "Tên gốc là “Aquilegia”, với gốc Latin “Aquila” mang nghĩa “đại bàng”, liên tưởng từ những cánh hoa hình móc câu như móng vuốt. Hoàng Liên Tím biểu trưng cho nỗi buồn và cho những người khổ hạnh—hoặc điên loạn. Mặc dù hoa mang vị ngọt và hoàn toàn ăn được, nhưng rễ và thân cây hoa lại mang độc tính cao. Người ăn phải sẽ bị viêm hệ tiêu hóa trầm trọng, dẫn đến triệu chứng đánh trống ngực nguy hiểm." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_3_DESC
TT 1838 "Cây Lay-ơn" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_4
TT 1839 "Mọc ở cả những khu vườn được chăm bẵm lẫn những cánh đồng cỏ um tùm, chi hoa này gồm nhiều loại có chứa độc tố, ngoại trừ một loại có thể vừa được dùng để nấu ăn, vừa được dùng để sắc thuốc. Bởi tán lá có hình thù tương tự như kiếm Giác Đấu, loài hoa này được mệnh danh là loài hoa của những anh hùng và võ sĩ giác đấu thời La Mã, tượng trưng cho sức mạnh và tráng kiện." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_4_DESC
TT 1840 "Táo Gai" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_5
TT 1841 "Một loài cây bụi dại có gai, dùng để đánh dấu ranh giới vườn tược và đất đai, và được coi là biểu tượng của hy vọng đến từ điều thận trọng. Nó đã góp mặt trong rất nhiều truyền thuyết, nổi danh nhất trong số đó là truyền thuyết về mão gai của Chúa. Khi đem đi sắc thuốc, loài cây này giúp điều tiết nhịp tim và chữa chứng thở gấp." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_5_DESC
TT 1842 "Hoa Ban Âu" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_6
TT 1843 "Trong tiếng Anh còn có tên gọi khác là “Saint John's herb”—“thảo mộc Thánh John”, loài hoa tượng trưng cho sự thù hận, nhưng cũng mang ý nghĩa che chở và ánh sáng. Hoa Ban Âu được dùng làm thuốc chữa trị các bệnh thần kinh. Dù mang biệt danh “hoa săn quỷ”, loài hoa này khiến người ăn vào gặp triệu chứng loạn nhịp tim hoặc tim đập nhanh." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_6_DESC
TT 1844 "Lavender" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_7
TT 1845 "Lavender is widely known for its perfume, and for its colour among weavers. The well-educated also use it in many cataplasms for its purifying values. It was rubbed on viper bites to weaken the venom, or on children's scalps to fight lice. Over time, it has become a symbol of dedication and loyalty." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_7_DESC
TT 1846 "Rhododendron" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_8
TT 1847 "While the rhododendron is harmless, honey made from its flowers is said to carry toxins with hallucinogenic and laxative properties. This is what seemingly thwarted the Greek army resulting in the Retreat of the Ten Thousand—the soldiers gorged themselves on this honey after looting and suffered its effects. Its apparent harmfulness is probably what made it a symbol of risk and danger." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_8_DESC
TT 1848 "Cinquefoils" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_9
TT 1849 "It owes its name to its number of petals—five, like the fingers on a hand. From a medicinal point of view, it was used from Antiquity in the form of pastes or decoctions to fight illnesses of the digestive tract, calm fever, and stop bleeding. It is also an important symbol in heraldry, decorating the coats of arms of the great families of north-west France." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_9_DESC
TT 1850 "Daffodil" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_10
TT 1851 "It is said that it grew from the remains of Narcissus, a mythological figure who died while looking at his own reflection. It symbolizes egoism and selfishness. Despite a marked toxic potential recognized by humanity since Antiquity, many European countries have used it to treat tumors, epilepsy, and hair loss—to varying degrees of success." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_10_DESC
TT 1852 "Black Nightshade" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_11
TT 1853 "A symbol of truth, associated by some with demonic witchcraft, the black nightshade has many worrisome nicknames: “devil's herb”, “death cherries”, and “beautiful death”. The toxicity of its berries is certainly a factor; consuming them can lead to death." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_11_DESC
TT 1854 "Rockfoils" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_12
TT 1855 "Saxifrage, also known as “stone-breaker”, is often found in cold, mountainous environments, seeping into rock crevices to avoid the frost. It symbolizes inevitability and a form of despair. This nickname comes from the fact that it was considered a means of dissolving kidney stones." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_12_DESC
TT 1856 "Christmas rose" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_13
TT 1857 "Used since Antiquity to treat dementia and some forms of paralysis, the plant quickly became a symbol of anxiety and disquiet—this is likely due to its toxicity, as handling it with one's bare hands causes violent irritations and even more severe reactions if ingested. Strangely enough, it is found in nativity scenes around Christmas. It was supposedly born from the tears of Madelon, a young shepherdess who was desperate to offer a gift to the newborn Christ." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_13_DESC
TT 1858 "Hugo's collection" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2
TT 1859 "Arrowhead" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_1
TT 1860 "This tiny, white star is a colony-forming aquatic wildflower often found in shallow lakes, and castle moats. Its genus name, “sagitta”, means “arrow” in Latin and comes from the shape of its leaves. It's also known as “Duck potato” as it produces corms, which are usually eaten stewed. It is said to absorb large amounts of heavy metallic elements such as copper or lead, two of the seven “pure metals” in alchemy." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_1_DESC
TT 1861 "Chamomile" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_2
TT 1862 "In the wild, it looks like tiny daisy heads, dotting the fields with blossoms of white and yellow. Traditionally, herbalists recommend it as a powerful sleep aid. Its protective properties are also supposed to cast out spells and its flowers are often associated with luck and financial success: many gamblers used to wash their hands in tea made from it to attract money." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_2_DESC
TT 1863 "Gentian" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_3
TT 1864 "According to Pliny the Elder, it gets its name from Gentius, last king of Illyria, who experienced its special healing effects when using it to clean wounds. Originating in the Alps, the roots of some species are turned into a sweet and sour liqueur, drunk as an appetiser for its purgative and bracing effects. Queen of the mountains, its bright, deep colour clearly relates to sorrow and pain. Offering a bouquet of Gentians will express your contempt." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_3_DESC
TT 1865 "Anemone" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_4
TT 1866 "Thriving on the shores of the Mediterranean, “Anemôné” in Greek means “daughter of the wind”. Also named Windflower, it blooms in heavy weather, then sows its feathery seeds across great distances. In Greek mythology, it is linked to abandonment and said to be born from the tears shed by the goddess Aphrodite when grieving Adonis' death. Peasants' beliefs tell that Amenone closing up is the sign of an impending rain." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_4_DESC
TT 1867 "Carnation" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_5
TT 1868 "The origins of the “flower of the gods” may reach back to antiquity. The Greeks used to offer “corone” (flower garlands) at coronation ceremonies and the Romans rewarded athletes with “Jupiter's Flowers” for outstanding performances. In Christian legends, Marie's tears turned into pink carnations as she was mourning her son and “carnis” would refer to the flesh of the Christ. Their bouquets, symbols of purity and gratitude, once honoured the love of a mother." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_5_DESC
TT 1869 "Jay" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_6
TT 1870 "Sentinel of the woods, its loud call warns all the creatures around when predators approach. Legend tells that it was once falsely accused by the other birds, and every one of them was sentenced to grant it one feather. Maybe that's why it's considered as the emblem of light, with its colourful, bright plumage, illuminating even the darkest places. If you find its feather, it will bring you the energy to heal and never give up." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_6_DESC
TT 1871 "Black headed gull" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_7
TT 1872 "Sociable and noisy, it usually flocks in open shorelines and dunes. It is of great significance to seamen and the shipwrecked out at sea: those who hear its call will sight land and be back home soon. In folktales, it symbolises maternal bonding. Dreaming of a gull is sign of a painful goodbye to the mother, while finding a feather from one would mean freedom and emancipation from the family." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_7_DESC
TT 1873 "Black kite" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_8
TT 1874 "As a scavenger, it is a fascinating yet misunderstood bird of prey with a low, strident call, and a graceful silhouette gliding in circles above lakes. In Greek mythology, it is associated with Apollo—the sun god—and embodies the gift of awareness and foresight. The kite's meaning is acceptance of the past and moving forward. If its feather pops up, you will soon experience a drastic change in your life." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_8_DESC
TT 1875 "Barn owl" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_9
TT 1876 "Ghostly pale with dark eyes, the white lady haunts abandoned barns or hollow logs and is commonly associated with prophecy and wisdom. Owning its feather connects you to your inner skills and gives the strength to take action in your life, while following your intuition. Crossing the path of this nocturnal hunter will also remind you that the world—even if dark and brutal—can still be filled with wonders." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_9_DESC
TT 1877 "Raven" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_10
TT 1878 "Since historical times, superstition associates it with bad omens and witchery, partly because of its disturbing, iridescent plumage but also because it makes a feast from any cadavers it comes across. ~A raven visiting in a dream is the symbol of self-transmutation: this spirit guide helps discover powers lying in the dark of our mind. Its feather brings the strength to overcome great changes and the promise of someone watching over us on life's challenging journey." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_10_DESC
TT 1879 "European goldfinch" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_11
TT 1880 "With its lovely song and brilliant lemon colour, this charming fellow must have gotten lost in the caves, as it usually lives on floodplains. It will visit your backyard if only you offer thistle seeds to peck—one of its common names is also 'thistle-finch'. In religious traditions, it symbolizes resurrection and liveliness while old pagan beliefs even thought it could bring a powerful protection against the scourge of the plague." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_11_DESC
TT 1881 "Greylag goose" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_12
TT 1882 "This ancestor of our farmyard goose can be found in many European wetlands. Long ago, in Rome, sacred geese of the temple of Juno used to warn of attacks as they were said to sense danger. In popular folklore, it also symbolises the call for adventure and journeys to legendary places. Its feathers, traditionally favoured for writing with, will remind you that you should follow your family and never forget your roots." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_12_DESC
